FT  26 APR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2 begins a week of 10-minute programmes commenting upon 40 of the 'best'
(whatever that means) pictures in British art galleries. Today in the first
episode of The Great Picture Trail Neil MacGregor, director of the National
Gallery, presents his choice of of eight, beginning with Titian's 'Three
Ages Of Man'. The paintings were selected for 'Sainsbury's Pictures For
Schools', a scheme providing 750 schools with framed prints and videos
(7.20). The expensive bickering between British Airways and Virgin
continues. World In Action reports on the price war between the two airlines
and the 'dirty tricks' campaign alleged to have been waged by BA (ITV 8.30).
Channel 4 launches a sequence of documentaries about television around the
world, Channels of Resistance (10.55) starts with 'Distress Signals' which
advances the well-worn thesis that television is becoming global without
becoming international: 'The danger is that one national style, the
American, will be imposed on all others with disastrous consequences for
indigenous production'.
