<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 93 / British Gas break-up opposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GAS Consumers Council has warned the government against breaking up
British Gas into separate companies as proposed by Ofgas, the industry
regulator.
Mr James Cooper, council chairman, said: 'No case has yet been made for
radical and irreversible restructuring.'
In the council's annual report published today, Mr Cooper says any
restructuring should show benefits for the consumer: 'Competition just for
the sake of competition is no reason for change.'
Proposals to break up British Gas are being considered by the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission, which is due to report in July.
The council said complaints from consumers about British Gas fell by 14 per
cent last year to 19,281 - the biggest drop since 1989. The council said
British Gas's reorganisation into district centres had led to improved
customer service.
But Ofgas registered an 89 per cent increase in complaints to 1,624 in its
annual report in February.
The disparity appears to result from Ofgas's higher public profile, which
has meant more complaints being directed towards it, rather than a rise in
consumer dissatisfaction.
Monopoly under the microscope, Page 14
