<DATE>930426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 93 / Where the main thrust of the DTI's new competitive policy
will be focused ...: Sectoral divisions
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
'MANDARINS meet the manufacturers' ran the headline on a DTI press release
issued last week to announce the arrival for work on the Rover production
line of two civil servants.
More usually, the two men form part of the DTI's vehicles division, one of
15 sectoral units set up a year ago to build a constructive partnership
between industry and government. Ten of the 19 people in the vehicles
division have on-line experience, with companies such as Honda, Nissan and
Unipart.
Their 'hands-on' experience represents the sharp end of Mr Heseltine's move
to win back for his department the respect of industry - the basis of his
ambitions to create a new partnership between the state and business.
The 15 divisions cover most of UK manufacturing and much of the service
sector - from vehicles, air, chemicals and steel to electronics, offshore
supplies, textiles and retailing to all the energy markets.
With the unmourned demise of the National Economic Development Office and
its own sector working groups, the intention is to use the DTI divisions as
a conduit between DTI and industry and as a source of quality market
intelligence to assist competitiveness at home and overseas. There will also
be plenty of emphasis on so-called benchmarking - continually comparing
company and industry performance against best practice and recommending ways
of improvement.
The ambition, according to a senior official with responsibility for some of
the industry divisions, is to make them so informed and knowledgeable that
the private sector will value their contribution. 'There has to be some
added value on our part. We cannot just parrot the views put to us by the
usual range of petitioners.'
He adds: 'When the managing director of a division of a major company feels
it is worthwhile to spend some time talking with someone in his sponsored
division we will be getting somewhere.'
The sectoral divisions are also expected to provide an important channel for
feeding industry's case into other parts of central government, offering
advice on the potential impact on business of other departmental proposals.
So far, so easy. The new regime will need time before it can be fairly
judged but the DTI acknowledges it still has much to do to earn its spurs
and to overturn the image of unhelpful, uninformed civil servants whose own
productivity is measured in vacuous conversations.
</TEXT>
