<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 93 / Heseltine's plan 'to help Britain win':  He is committed to
revitalising the relationship between the government and industry. A year
ago the trade and industry secretary promised a new industrial strategy.
After being sidetracked by the pit closure debate, this blueprint is largely
completed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HESELTINE, trade and industry secretary, is in search of respect.
He runs a department used to being sidelined by its political masters and
sneered at by the industries it is supposed to sponsor.
Last week, flanked by his six department ministers and his most senior civil
servants, he gave the Financial Times a detailed insight into the proposals
he is now putting into force 'to help British companies win'.
He believes the Department of Trade and Industry and its 12,450 staff have a
critical role in building a beefy British economy. But he knows the DTI's
reputation is ragged and that low morale has led many bright minds to
defect.
His task, overshadowed while the government dug itself out of the
pit-closure crisis, is to establish the DTI's authority in government and
industry; to place it at the hub of a national effort to make Britain fully
competitive in a cut-throat world.
His message to the FT was a mix of realism and enthusiasm, delivered with a
distinct Heseltine flourish, in spite of his insistence that it had not been
polished up, party conference-style, for his audience.
He stressed that his plans are long-term. They will have to be, given the
inertia to overcome, the damage to be undone and the findings of an
unpublished DTI report which says Britain's product base is weak and still
deteriorating. It, like Mr Heseltine, talks in terms of decades of
reconstruction. He dismisses gimmicks and magic solutions and talks only of
a mutual partnership with the wealth-creating sector, not of intervening at
every meal time.
His partnership, however, will not be based on cosy conversations with 'the
self-selecting elite' of big business but will embrace as many as possible
of Britain's 3m companies.
Hence his plans for a national chain of 'one-stop' advice shops for
businesses, derided by critics as another, inconsequential player in the
bewildering complex of agencies and outlets the government likes to set up.
But to Mr Heseltine, his shops are 'an idea whose time has come', a small
but important vanguard in what he says is the march towards a cultural
revolution in business and government.
Manufacturing companies have to innovate, market, get off their behinds and
go for it; government has to act as a catalyst for elements of national
self-interest and to think more carefully before it legislates in a way
which could harm business. He wants to be industry's 'friend at court'.
A man with his fair share of political enemies - but who retains a powerful
pull in cabinet and the trust of the prime minister - he does not want to
enlist any more. His evangelising will be polite but pervasive, in
Westminster and Europe. 'We will not adopt a confrontational role. That is
the way to lose influence, to close doors.'
He is certainly 'not prepared to have a punch-up with the Treasury, although
that does not mean they win all the time'. He adds: 'You are not going to
hear from me when I win. No doubt you will hear from them when I don't'
Mr Heseltine once spoke of investing in the DTI powers to rival those of the
Treasury, which dispenses to him a tiny annual budget - little more than
Pounds 1bn against Pounds 65bn for social security. It is not planning to
give him any more.
No problem. 'We do not seek to put large sums of money on the table in order
to buy an objective.' Government's role must be limited, he emphasises.
While it can climb on board to help promote industrial success, free
enterprise is in the driving seat.
Government should certainly provide some of the critical ingredients, like
sound macro-economic management, high-quality education and good transport
infrastructure. None of these is his direct responsibility and all are
subject to harsh criticism.
His underlying theme, the formula for success, is competitiveness, between
companies and between countries. Britain, in spite of some progress in the
1980s, lies 18th in the 24-nation OECD league of competitiveness. Though Mr
Heseltine admits people cannot agree on a definition, competitiveness now
represents - if such concepts are permitted - his government's industrial
policy. With it, he says, will come a critical leg-up for a national
exporting effort which is impressive but nowhere near impressive enough.
Selling overseas is to be a prime focus for the DTI, with the department's
exporting operations about to undergo a fundamental restructuring. Mr
Heseltine is happy to resurrect old, corporatist language to talk of
'national champions', though strictly in the context of export drives. 'I
would be prepared to decide what is more likely to win in the circumstances
and will put all our resources behind it. If I can help to fight on one
front then I will.'
But the first task, he says, is to establish industry's strengths and
weaknesses. On his arrival a year ago, he told his officials to get on
aircraft and 'case the world', firstly to see what the competition is up to
and then to assess, with British industry, the strategic, longer-term issues
it faces.
'Information is critical. Because on the quality of the information we
gather, the respect of industry depends. If we are known to understand, to
be aware, to have views that are coherent, thought through, well-informed,
then industry will take this department seriously'.
At the heart of his mission to understand and his plans for partnership are
the 15 sectoral divisions set up last July to shadow large chunks of British
industry. Though he once also wanted a revitalised National Economic
Development Organisation, which ran its own sector working groups, he denies
its closure was a personal defeat. He says he supported Mr Norman Lamont,
the chancellor, in killing it off.
'My department is now doing what Nedo should have been doing on a scale
beyond the wildest dreams of Nedo's architects'. It was always kept at the
margins of government, he stresses, while his sector operations will be at
the heart of it.
Under Mr Heseltine's plan, his own department will, for example, have to be
fully abreast of state-of-the-art aerospace technology. 'We are constantly
being asked for project launch aid and I would expect people here advising
ministers to be experts in leading edge technology, knowing where its going
to be in 10 years time'.
As you spend money on frontier-type research, he says, it is vital you ask
questions as you go. 'Should you just be reactive to one scheme someone puts
up or should you have a view about where it's taking you?' Ask some
applicants about the spin-off from their activities to other sectors of the
economy and they have no idea, he shrugs.
But though Mr Heseltine has some officials on board capable of such
dialogue, he is going outside to find personnel with 'street cred'. There
are now more than 50 private-sector secondees in the DTI and more will
follow. The plan is to recruit 100 exporting experts alone.
His plans, though presented in modest, worldly-wise tones, are ambitious and
his efforts could sink in the sea of good intentions surrounding Britain's
industrial decline.
He is not prime minister, able to orchestrate from the centre, though the
prime minister on Friday publicly backed him to the hilt.
Mr Heseltine claims there has already been a sea-change in government
language and that it is seeping through the government machinery, though
there are ministers happy enough to frustrate him. Industrialists cannot
deny that much of what they have recently sought has been granted. He
expects and relishes a hard slog. 'I cannot do it faster, unless I want to
do it in a dirigiste, proscriptive way. That's disaster.
How on earth, the eighth secretary of state for trade and industry in 10
years is asked, are you going to sell this cultural change? 'I'm going to
stay here,' he chuckles.
</TEXT>
<XX>
