<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 93 / Spirit of the Blitz recalled as City vows to beat bombers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN and PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VERA LYNN may have given way to Gordon Gecko years ago, but the spirit of
the Blitz returned to the City of London yesterday. There were other
reminders: the innocent victims, an unseen enemy, and those with an eye for
the main chance.
An army of repair contractors' lorries queued at first light down London
Wall, waiting for the off. 'It was like the troops waiting to embark on
D-Day,' said a Guildhall official. Platoons of glaziers had started out for
the City before first light.
By 7am, as key holders moved among the rubble and police cordons in the
drizzle, about 200 contractors were waiting at the door of the Guildhall.
City landlords were on hand offering office space to those displaced by the
blast. Two hours later the crowd had swelled to 600.
Inside the Lord Mayor was telling the world that while the pictures told a
story of devastation the spirit of London would beat the terrorists.
Throughout the day he held the line.
