<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 93 / Britain oversaw EBRD's spending on HQ
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK was the only government represented on the building committee which
oversaw the spending of Pounds 55.5m on fitting the new headquarters of the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
However, Mr Nicholas Bailey, the official at the Overseas Development
Administration on the committee, was powerless to prevent spending on new
marble, wood panelling and other 'luxuries' because the government had
provided a Pounds 40m building grant to the EBRD with no conditions
attached, according to a UK official.
It also emerged yesterday that officials from the EBRD's shareholder
governments, led by the Germans, are exploring the possibility of creating a
new post of chief executive at the bank to back up Mr Jacques Attali, the
bank's president.
The idea of appointing an EBRD chief executive has not yet been put forward
by Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister. The suggestion would be
designed to improve the organisational structure of the bank following
criticisms of insufficient budgetary control.
None of the other countries which own the bank were represented on the
building committee, chaired by the bank's budget director, Mr Pierre
Pissaloux. The UK was on the committee because of the Pounds 40m grant,
which was given to the bank as an incentive to locate in London.
'After the EBRD's director approved the budget (at the end of 1991), there
was nothing we could do (about how the money was spent)', said the official.
'It was a nightmare.' The UK's role in the building project would probably
be examined by the auditor general, Sir John Bourn, an official said.
It also emerged yesterday that the architects working on the project,
Berthet &amp; Pochy of France, were appointed on the insistence of the bank and
without following the public tendering procedures which usually apply to
public sector projects, according to a UK government official.
Mrs Marion Pochy, the wife of one of Berthet &amp; Pochy's founders, painted a
mural at the bank's headquarters in collaboration with two east European
artists. They are understood to have been paid less than Pounds 30,000.
Meanwhile, the bank's directors, which represent the countries which own the
bank, have asked for details of a spacious EBRD office in Paris, which is
used principally by Mr Attali.
Many directors did not know of the existence of the office, which is in a
renovated 19th century palace in the Boulevard Madeleine, until last week.
The EBRD said yesterday that the rent on the Paris office was paid by the
French government and referred calls to Mr Jean-Claude Trichet, the director
of the French Treasury. However, his office said the finance ministry had
paid the rent up to May last year and had no idea who had been paying the
rent since then. Bank sources said late last night that the bill was now
being paid by the French foreign ministry.
Civil servant powerless, Page 3
Jumping flash Jacques, Page 6
</TEXT>
