<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 93 / UK Company News: Lopex bounces back and looks to resume
dividends
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOPEX, the communications group, returned pre-tax profits of Pounds 210,000
in the year to end-December against previous losses of Pounds 398,000.
Directors do not recommend a dividend, but said they would propose a final
dividend for 1993 'in the absence of unforeseen circumstances'. The last
payment was a final for the 1990 year.
The preliminary results include a pro forma balance sheet adjusted for a
Pounds 3.5m rights issue in February this year, which moved cash up to
Pounds 7.89m (Pounds 4.35m), and the sale of its stake in a Dutch business.
Also long term obligations fell to Pounds 5.91m (Pounds 7.46m in the 1992
balance sheet) because of the conversion of a long term bonus for employees
into shares. Investments fell to Pounds 2.13m (Pounds 2.27m).
Turnover, which includes the cost of advertising space ultimately paid by
customers, fell to Pounds 146m (Pounds 206m). The company said stripping out
disposals the comparative figure for 1991 was Pounds 155m. Revenue -
commission on sales - fell to Pounds 41.1m (Pounds 58.7m).
Lopex made an exceptional provision for redundancy costs of Pounds 594,000
(Pounds 1.28m), partly offset by the release of a reorganisation provision
of Pounds 421,000.
It also made an extraordinary provision of Pounds 548,000 (gain Pounds
1.86m) covering the loss on sale or closure of discontinued operations,
including goodwill originally written off to reserves but included in the
acquisition considerations.
The company paid interest of Pounds 950,000 (Pounds 2.03m), but after
interest and dividends received the net charge was Pounds 693,000 (Pounds
1.49m). The company's share of profits in associated companies, less losses,
fell to Pounds 105,000 (Pounds 316,000).
The loss per share fell from 4.76p to 0.21p.
</TEXT>
