<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 93 / Building societies see steady upturn . . . but agents
disagree
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FURTHER EVIDENCE of a steady recovery in the housing market emerged
yesterday when building societies disclosed that the value of housebuyers'
commitments to buy mortgages rose for the second month running in March.
However, the reports below from FT writers in the regions show that many
estate agents in England and Wales see only a patchy recovery and are
cautious about house prices.
The rise in commitments emerged in spite of an announcement this week from
the rival Abbey National, the mortgage lender, that its commitments rose 60
per cent in the first quarter.
Net new commitments rose to Pounds 3.09bn in March from Pounds 2.72bn in
February and Pounds 1.55bn in January. However, the March figure was below
that of the same month last year, when it was Pounds 3.46bn.
Mr Mark Boleat, Building Societies Association director-general, said
reports of rises in activity suggested that lending would continue to
increase.
Mr John Wriglesworth, UBS analyst, said the increase in net new commitments
was significant in spite of the fact that the total for the first quarter
was only Pounds 7.36m compared with Pounds 8.43m for the same period last
year.
Mr Boleat said the rise in house activity had also helped societies to
increase their inflow of retail funds because individuals selling homes had
capital available.
Societies' net retail inflow in March was Pounds 249m, following an inflow
of Pounds 208m in February and Pounds 363m in January. The total for the
quarter at Pounds 820m was well up on the first quarter of last year, when
societies achieved an inflow of Pounds 266m.
Societies are worried that they face strong competition for retail funds
from the government's National Savings products and from equity products.
Last year's total retail inflow of a net Pounds 295m was well below inflows
in previous years.
Housebuilders have also reported significant increases in net reservations -
agreed sales on which a deposit has been paid less any cancellations. A
survey of 15 of the country's largest builders conducted by the
Housebuilders Federation showed that net reservations rose by a third during
the first 15 weeks of this year compared with the corresponding period last
year.
The biggest rise in sales has been to first-time buyers. Recently there have
been signs that sales of houses in the medium-price bracket have also
started to improve, said Mr Joe Dwyer, chief executive of Wimpey, the
housebuilder. He said: 'The improvement is from a very low base and it is
still too early to talk of a sustained recovery. Nonetheless things are
looking better.'
The government has asked Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair
trading, to make the National House Building Council amend its structural
warranty scheme for new homes so that builders can use comparable
alternative ones.
</TEXT>
