<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 93 / NUM to renew court challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Union of Mineworkers is to mount a further High Court challenge
to British Coal's pit closure programme, claiming redundancy terms being
offered to miners at nine threatened pits are in breach of an assurance
given by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, John Mason
writes.
The NUM was yesterday given leave by Mr Justice Popplewell to seek a
judicial review of the corporation's voluntary redundancy arrangements at
the nine pits which form the second tranche in the closure programme. The
hearing will be heard on May 5.
The union is claiming British Coal is offering the maximum possible
redundancy payments to miners who choose to leave before the end of the
current consultation period over the pit closure programme.
However, miners have been warned that those made redundant after the end of
the consultation period will be eligible for only minimum payments.
