<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 93 / Shortfall in G7's aid for Russia predicted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OFFICIAL financial support for Russia this year from the Group of Seven
countries is likely to fall short of the Dollars 43.4bn (Pounds 28.1bn)
pledged at the recent G7 meeting in Tokyo, according to the Institute of
International Finance.
The IIF, a Washington-based economic research body founded by leading
international banks, believes that only Dollars 32bn of official western
support will be provided this year, largely because it expects International
Monetary Fund disbursements will reach only Dollars 4bn compared with the
Dollars 13.1bn IMF total agreed in Tokyo.
Mr Anthony Bottrill, IIF deputy managing director, said in London yesterday
that half the planned IMF standby facility of Dollars 4bn might be disbursed
this year together with half the new Dollars 3bn 'systemic transition
facility' that was agreed in Tokyo. The IIF does not expect Russia to
qualify for the Dollars 6bn rouble stabilisation fund first promised by the
G7 last year and included in the Tokyo package.
The IIF has calculated that western official support for Russia last year
totalled Dollars 17.55bn, compared with a promised Dollars 24bn. While the
Dollars 1bn of finance supplied by the IMF was Dollars 9bn less than
projected, largely because of the non-activation of the stabilisation fund,
official debt rescheduling was higher than expected and made up most of the
shortfall.
But Mr Bottrill said capital flight from Russia undid the good provided by
western finance last year - an estimated Dollars 8bn in 1992, with funds
leaving Russia at a rate a rate of Dollars 1bn a month from the end of the
first quarter onwards.
As much as Dollars 1.5bn of flight capital may have flowed into Russia in
the first quarter of 1992, when tight fiscal and monetary policies were in
place. IIF economists believe capital reflows will only resume after Russia
has significantly raised interest rates and oil prices.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
